{"key":"post-9515640","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9515640</id>\n<content>We all know cubensis doesn't even require a casing layer, so it's really moot to argue one way or the other what is best.&amp;nbsp; With species that DO require a casing layer to fruit, plain verm won't cut the mustard.&amp;nbsp; There's beneficial bacteria in peat that help stimulate pinsets, which are missing with verm.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I've ruffled a lot of feathers lately by stating verm is a nutritious food for fungi.&amp;nbsp; We all know plain verm casing layers will support cobweb, but they also support cubensis and many other species of beneficial fungi.&amp;nbsp; You can take a small jar of grain spawn, mix it well with verm, and get a huge flush.&amp;nbsp; It's not as good as coir or horse manure, but verm definitely isn't inert, even though it's mineral. It's a great addition to any substrate material, and not just for holding water. Go figure.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9516679</next>\n<prev>9515459</prev>\n<first>8648068</first>\n<last>9516679</last>\n<when>1230619532</when>\n<utime>12/30/08 08:45 AM</utime>\n</post>"}